# D.3 Program Development


## Object-Oriented Programming Concepts


Object-oriented programming (OOP) is a fundamental paradigm in modern software development. Let's break down the key concepts:

### Classes and Objects


A class is a blueprint for creating objects. It defines the attributes (data) and methods (behaviors) that objects of that class will have.

<callout type="example">Consider a `Car` class:
<pre>public class Car {
    private String make;
    private String model;
    private int year;

    public void startEngine() {
        System.out.println("Engine started!");
    }
}
</pre>
An object is an instance of a class:
<pre>Car myCar = new Car();
myCar.startEngine();
</pre></callout>

### Encapsulation


Encapsulation is the bundling of data and the methods that operate on that data within a single unit (class). It restricts direct access to some of an object's components, which is a means of preventing accidental interference and misuse of the methods and data.

<callout type="tip">Use private access modifiers for fields and provide public getter and setter methods to control access to those fields.</callout>

### Inheritance


Inheritance allows a class to inherit properties and methods from another class. It promotes code reuse and establishes a relationship between a more general class (superclass) and a more specialized class (subclass).

<callout type="example"><pre>public class ElectricCar extends Car {
    private int batteryCapacity;

    public void chargeBattery() {
        System.out.println("Battery charging...");
    }
}
</pre></callout>

### Polymorphism


Polymorphism allows objects of different classes to be treated as objects of a common superclass. It enables a single interface to represent different underlying forms (data types).

<callout type="example"><pre>Car[] carLot = new Car[3];
carLot[0] = new Car();
carLot[1] = new ElectricCar();
carLot[2] = new HybridCar();

for (Car car : carLot) {
    car.startEngine(); // Each car type may implement this differently
}
</pre></callout>

## UML Diagrams


Unified Modeling Language (UML) diagrams are visual representations of software systems. They help in designing, documenting, and communicating about object-oriented systems.

### Class Diagrams


Class diagrams show the static structure of a system, including classes, their attributes, methods, and the relationships between classes.

_A class diagram showing relationships between Car, ElectricCar, and HybridCar classes_

### Object Diagrams


Object diagrams show instances of classes (objects) at a specific point in time.

_An object diagram showing specific instances of Car and ElectricCar_

## Advanced OOP Concepts


### Recursion


Recursion is a programming technique where a function calls itself to solve a problem by breaking it down into smaller, similar subproblems.

<callout type="example">Calculating factorial using recursion:
<pre>public static int factorial(int n) {
    if (n == 0 || n == 1) {
        return 1;
    }
    return n * factorial(n - 1);
}
</pre></callout>

<callout type="note">While powerful, recursion can lead to stack overflow errors if not implemented carefully. Always ensure there's a base case to stop the recursion.</callout>

### Object References


In Java, variables of object types don't directly contain the object's data. Instead, they contain a reference (essentially an address) to where the object is stored in memory.

<callout type="example"><pre>Car car1 = new Car();
Car car2 = car1; // car2 now references the same object as car1
</pre></callout>

### Abstract Data Types (ADTs)


ADTs are mathematical models for data types where the data type is defined by its behavior from the point of view of a user of the data, specifically in terms of possible values, possible operations on data of this type, and the behavior of these operations.

Common ADTs include:

1. List
2. Stack
3. Queue
4. Tree

<callout type="example">Implementing a Stack ADT:
<pre>public class Stack

