## Programming Style and Naming Conventions


Adhering to consistent programming style and naming conventions is crucial for code readability and maintainability.

### Naming Conventions


* Class names should start with an uppercase letter and use CamelCase (e.g., `CarFactory`)
* Method and variable names should start with a lowercase letter and use camelCase (e.g., `startEngine`)
* Constants should be in all uppercase with words separated by underscores (e.g., `MAX_SPEED`)

### Code Formatting


* Use consistent indentation (typically 4 spaces or 1 tab)
* Place opening braces on the same line as the declaration
* Use blank lines to separate logical blocks of code

<callout type="tip">Many IDEs offer auto-formatting features. Use them to maintain consistent code style across your project.</callout>

### Comments and Documentation


* Use JavaDoc comments for classes and public methods
* Use inline comments sparingly, only when the code's purpose isn't immediately clear

<callout type="example"><pre>/**
 * Represents a car in the dealership inventory.
 */
public class Car {
    private String vin; // Vehicle Identification Number

    /**
     * Starts the car's engine.
     * @return true if the engine started successfully, false otherwise
     */
    public boolean startEngine() {
        // Implementation details...
    }
}
</pre></callout>

By following these principles and practices, developers can create more robust, maintainable, and scalable object-oriented programs. Remember that good programming is not just about making the code work, but also about making it understandable and modifiable for future developers (including yourself!).
